  "market_context": "Top-down analysis of a prior trade on the indices triad (NQ, ES, YM). On the weekly, all three indices traded into a prior high; on the daily, the same sequence repeats with the middle asset (ES) breaking SMT while the third (YM) diverges.",
  "key_observation": "When the weakest/lagging asset catches up to a prior high and breaks the SMT divergence, that SMT failure itself becomes the reversal trigger. The pattern is fractal — it shows on weekly, and an even higher-probability version appears on the daily.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Open the indices triad (NQ, ES, YM) on the weekly timeframe to set HTF context for the trade.",
    "Mark the same prior swing high across NQ, ES, and YM and note that YM clearly failed to manipulate it, creating SMT divergence with NQ and ES.",
    "Conclude that once the weakest asset eventually catches up to the SMT level and breaks it, the market is set up to potentially reverse.",
    "Drop down to the daily timeframe on the same triad and mark the equivalent highs to look for the same SMT sequence.",
    "Observe that ES traded into the high (creating SMT with YM) while NQ clearly failed to manipulate the same high, leaving NQ as the lagging asset.",
    "Note that on the daily this is the higher-probability variant: the middle asset (ES) breaking the SMT is the trigger while the third asset (YM) creates the divergence.",
    "Contrast with the weekly variant where all markets break the SMT and the lagging asset's catch-up is the trigger, then prepare to drop to the 4H for the daily profile."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "SMT failures are themselves the reversal trigger: when the lagging asset finally catches up to a divergent high (or the middle asset breaks SMT while a third diverges), expect reversal. The signature is fractal across weekly and daily timeframes.",
